Notes on dark-frame treatment and hot-pixel handling

Two different approaches to hot-pixel handling in dark frames were evaluated. In the first approach (this work), hot pixels are identified and retained as a boolean mask on each individual dark frame. During combination, masked pixels are excluded from the statistical estimator (median with sigma clipping), and the bad-pixel information is preserved in the final master dark. This ensures that pixels known to be unreliable are not trusted at any stage of calibration and can be consistently ignored in downstream processing.

In the alternative approach, hot and cold pixels are identified using a global threshold and replaced via local interpolation prior to creating the master dark. This produces a visually clean calibration frame but removes any record of which pixels were originally defective. While this method is suitable for cosmetic correction or visualization, it introduces interpolated values into the calibration data and eliminates the ability to track or propagate bad-pixel information.

For precision calibration and scientific measurements, preserving bad-pixel masks is preferred over interpolating pixel values. Mask-based approaches avoid introducing artificial signal and allow subsequent reduction steps to make informed decisions about pixel reliability.

