			Let 
			R = \text{raw science image, which contains signal } S, \text{ dark } D, \text{ and pixel sensitivity } g(x, y): \quad R = g (S + D) \quad \text{(simplified)}
			Flats were dark-subtracted before combining, so the master flat is approximately
			F \approx g \quad \text{(normalized to ~1)}.
			If you divide the raw frame by the master flat:
			\frac{R}{F} \approx \frac{g (S + D)}{g} = S + D
			The dark term \(D\) remains — division cancels the gain pattern but does **not** subtract the additive dark term.
			To remove the dark, you must subtract it first:
			\frac{R - D}{F} \approx \frac{g S}{g} = S
			That is why the background near ~60 ADU persists in `raw / combined_flat` even when the flats themselves had their dark removed.
