The FWHM that you read is very much dependant on Binning. This is why:
	Binning combines multiple camera pixels into one larger “super-pixel,” so with 3×3 binning, each pixel covers nine times more sky area. This makes stars appear smaller in pixel units — the measured FWHM in pixels decreases roughly in proportion to the binning factor (e.g., 6 px at 1×1 becomes about 2 px at 3×3). However, because each binned pixel covers a larger angular size, the true FWHM in arcseconds (seeing) remains the same once the pixel scale is adjusted for binning. In practice, 1×1 binning gives the most precise FWHM measurements since the star is sampled by more pixels, while higher binning trades some spatial resolution for improved signal-to-noise.

