4. Understanding Index Files
	Astrometry.net uses index files to match star patterns in your image to known star positions from catalogs (e.g., Tycho-2, Gaia).
	Selecting appropriate index files is crucial for successful astrometric solving. Index files are pre-built for various field sizes 
	and sky regions.
   Choosing the Right Index Files
	Field of View (FOV) is Key: The most important factor in index file selection is the angular size of your image’s field of view
	(e.g., 4x4 arcminutes).

   The 20% Rule (Guideline): A general recommendation is to select index files with “skymark” diameters roughly equal to 20% of the 
	narrowest dimension of your FOV. This guideline balances sufficient landmark coverage with avoiding crowding or sparsity. For a 4x4 
	arcminute FOV, this suggests skymarks around 0.8 arcminutes.

   5200-Series Files (Narrow Fields): The 5200-series is designed for fields of view smaller than 1 degree (60 arcminutes). These are built 
	from the Tycho-2 and Gaia catalogs.

   Skymark Diameters for 5200 series: Files with the tag ‘index-5200’ have skymark diameters in the range of 2.0-2.8 arcminutes 1.

   5200 Series is a close choice: Since it is designed for images narrower than 1 degree and contain skymark diameters that is close
	to the 0.8 arcminutes recommendation, the 5200-series is a good one to start with.

   Individual Sky Tiles: Each file in the range index-5200-00.fits to index-5200-47.fits represents a different “tile” covering a
	specific region of the sky. To ensure coverage no matter where your image is pointed, download all the files in this range. This is achieved by using the hpsplit program with the -n 2 option 5. This configuration divides the sky into 48 distinct regions.

If Standard Files Don’t Work
	Consider Custom Index Files: For very small fields of view or unusual setups, you might need to create custom index files tailored
to your specific image parameters. This involves using specialized software and star catalogs.
