>>> What are Index Files?
Imagine you have a HUGE map of the entire sky, showing the positions of millions of stars. But this map isn’t like a paper map;
it’s stored inside your computer as a big list of numbers. Now, imagine you take a picture of a small part of the sky with your telescope.
Your picture shows some stars, but you don’t know exactly where on the big map your picture is located. That’s where index files come in. 
An index file is like a cheat sheet that helps astrometry.net quickly find the matching area on the BIG map.

What’s Inside an Index File?
Instead of storing the positions of every star, an index file stores patterns of stars. It looks for small groups of stars (usually 3 or 4)
and calculates the angles and distances between them. It then stores these patterns, along with the exact location of that pattern on the
big sky map. Think of it as constellations with precise coordinates.
	*Pattern Matching: When you give astrometry.net your image, it also looks for star patterns in your image.
	* Finding a Match: astrometry.net compares the star patterns in your image to the patterns stored in the index files. If it finds a match,
		it knows approximately where your image is located on the big sky map.
	* Calculating WCS: Once astrometry.net has a good match, it can precisely calculate the World Coordinate System (WCS) for your image. 
		The WCS is the link between the pixels in your image and the real coordinates (Right Ascension and Declination) on the sky. It allows 
		you to say, “This pixel in my image corresponds to this specific location in the sky.”

