#  14030120 - 3: Apperture Photometry
Following the tutorial located at: https://photutils.readthedocs.io/en/stable/aperture.html
The aperture_photometry() function and the ApertureStats class are the main tools to perform aperture
photometry on an astronomical image for a given set of apertures.

   Of course there are two ways to define Apertures for photometry:
      - Pixel-based apertures are defined in terms of the number of pixels in the aperture. This is 
         the simplest type of aperture to use, but it can be inaccurate if the pixels are not square.
      - Sky-based apertures are defined in terms of the angular size of the aperture on the sky. 
         This is a more accurate way to define an aperture, but it can be more difficult to use, 
         especially if the image is not well-calibrated.

   1. The first step in performing aperture photometry is to create an aperture object (Define Apertures). 
   An aperture object is defined by a position (or a list of positions) and parameters that define its size 
   and possibly, orientation (e.g., an elliptical aperture).

